DID YOU KNOW? Drishti (focal point/ gaze) is part of the Tristana Method (three fold approach to asana practice) along with breath and bandha! They include: 
1 – Tip of the nose – Nasagra Drishti
2 – Up to space – Urdva Drishti
3 – Third Eye – Brumadya Drishti
4 – Tip of the middle finger – Hastagra Drishti
5 – Tip of the thumb – Angushta Drishti
6 – Right Side – Parshva Drishti
7 – Left Side – Parshva Drishti
8 – Navel – Nabi Drishti 
9 – Tip of the big toe – Padagra Drishti 
THE MORE YOU KNOW. THANKS FOR LISTENING! (Plz excuse the incorrect captions) 
#yogapractice #ashtangayoga #vinyasayoga #ashtangavinyasa #ashtangis #yogamom #tristanamethod

Some tips for ARDHA (half) BADDHA (bound) PADMOTTANASANA (lotus forward fold) or any time you’re practicing lotus pose for that matter … by the way I swear I rescued cc after this video 😂😂😂 ignore the bad captions lol 

1. DO make sure to open your hip to the side to place the foot on top of the thighs 
2. DON’T cross the ankle over the thigh in thinking you will be able to grab the foot easier that way. This could be dangerous for the knee. 
3. DO try to extend the arm more by lifting it up before going around the back 
4. DO use modifications!!! Yoga straps are too long and unnecessary for this pose. Grab a towel, a burp cloth, a tie, whatever is lying around. You can roll that shit up to place behind the knee too if you ever have any pain from overextension. 
5. DON’T feel the need to push the knee down right away. You can try to do it while folding forward. 
6. DO remember to take that extra inhale and exhale on the way back up!! 

Any other tips teachers? Let me know in the comments 🙌🏻🤙🏼💙

There are a lot of excuses around ashtanga yoga. I am guilty of some myself…

“No Music?” 
“The Same Sequence every time!?” 
“It’s too intense.”
“I don’t have enough time” 
“I’m not flexible enough” 

The thing is, this practice can seem intimidating on the outside… Sure we have a lot of crazy “rules” but who says you have to follow the call?

Ashtanga is perfect for adapting and adjusting to each persons individual needs. Want to go slower? Perfect. Need more? This is for you. Need modifications? Spoiler alert: we actually have them. Feel like putting on music? Who’s gonna stop you?? 

Start by learning these amazing standing postures. Soon it becomes second nature. All you need is 20 minutes. No video, no studio, just you and yourself. Add on as you see fit. 

Want to develop a self practice you will have for life? Feel like coming to paradise for a week? Join me for my Ashtanga Yoga Intensive Training. Fit for anyone. March 20-27 in Nicaragua with @yogaacademyinternational. Meals and your stay are included. Link in my bio 🙏🤙🏼💙 #ashtanga

HOW TO: Sirsasana Headstand!
*Make sure you have a steady and strong asana practice before trying this pose. Save your neck and your back, no rush!! This requires a lot of hamstring flexibility, core and upper body strength… 
*get into your dolphin position first (if it’s too difficult to hold this, practice for a while before attempting a headstand. 
*Keep elbows directly underneath shoulders. 
*Interlace fingers and begin to walk your feet in at the same time directing the top of your head onto the mat. 
*One the hips are directly over the shoulders you should feel a natural lightness in the feet. If this isn’t happening it’s most likely because of hamstring flexibility. Give it time! 
*Don’t jump or kick up! Try walking up slowly first before giving yourself that extra push. 

A wall could work for support… but the best support is a HUMAN! A teacher, in fact! This is one of my favorite asanas to help students with 🥹

Did you know, yoga isn’t just about stretching and exercising?? 
In The Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, there is an 8 fold path to yoga called ASHTANGA which isn’t all about handstands! 😳🤔. It’s true! 
Did I blow your mind? 🤯 

They are:

1. YAMA – Restraints, moral disciplines or moral vows
2. NIYAMA – Positive duties or observances
3. ASANA – Posture
4. PRANAYAMA – Breathing Techniques
5. PRATYAHARA – Sense withdrawal
6. DHARANA – Focused Concentration
7. DHYANA – Meditative Absorption 
8. SAMADHI – Enlightenment

Check it out! Go read about it! 
Comment below if you have a favorite book on the sutras! 🤘🏻🙏💙.
Should I post more on yoga philosophy?

Hey everybody! This is yoga too!! Do you have a favorite? How are you implementing the Yamas into your daily life as a “yogi” or a “yoga teacher”? Something I’ve been asking myself for a decade now. Always good to step back and focus on the other 7 limbs of yoga 🧘🏼‍♀️ 🤘🏻😎⛰️ #yamas #yamasandniyamas #yogaphilosophy #ashtangayoga

The second limb of yoga is Niyamas! These are positive duties or habits for healthy living. Do you observe the Niyamas in your daily life? How do you take your yoga off the mat? Do you teach these in your classes? They are:
* Saucha – purity, cleanliness
* Santosha – contentment, gratitude
* Tapas – discipline, inner fire
* Svādhyāya – self-reflection, self-study 
* Īśvara Pranidhāna – devotion, surrender to a higher power (god or self)
#niyamas #ashtanga #ashtangayoga #yoga #yogaphilosophy #yogateachers #yogalife

Hey ig world… Since I’m back in the NJ yoga scene after 10 whole years, I thought it’d be a good time to drop some yoga facts about me for my new friends… 

🖤 I took my first trip to india in 2012 to study in Goa and received my 200hr yttc. I returned in 2015 to get my 500 hour and that same year I took my first trip to Mysore to study Ashtanga. I’d never practiced mysore style before. I just wanted to go learn more Ashtanga, so I went. 😎 living in Abu Dhabi at the time, my frequent trips were much easier with the closer distance and my flexible work schedule. 

🖤 In 2017 Sharathji gave me his authorization to teach (after 4 mysore trips) and I have been back 6x: a total of 9 trips to india over the last decade. 8 of those trips were for yoga related trainings. One was for a wedding 🤩. 

🖤 I have studied and practiced Ashtanga all over the world with many amazing teachers. I am so grateful to them all. 

🖤 I have taught workshops, trainings, classes, and private lessons in over 11 different countries! And I’ve been to 32. I love to travel 🙃. 

🖤 I was an expat for 9 years (one in Canada and 8 in UAE 🇦🇪) but now I am back in New Jersey! 

🖤 I am currently staying home with two kiddos (1 and 4) so I don’t have a busy teaching schedule BUT you can take my online course with @yogaacademyinternational or stay tuned for pop ups and up-coming trainings! 

🖤 Next led class @holdingspace_collective is August 19th at 9am. Excited to bring traditional Ashtanga to the Jersey shore!

🖤 Follow @ashtangayoganj for more class stuff!

Have you heard of the “Tristana Method”? This is the three-fold approach to asana (physically doing yoga poses) in the Ashtanga Yoga practice. It combines 1. Breath 2. Bandhas (energy/ body locks) 3. Drishti or focal point (there are nine different ones!). The combination of this takes the physical practice from a work-out to an entire mind-body experience. 

If you live nearby the Jersey Shore, I’m teaching a 25-hour Intensive in Avon with @ashtangayoganj where you can come and hear me chat away about stuff like this. Come discuss ashtanga yoga philosophy, asana, pranayama, history, Sanskrit, mantras, culture, adjustments, and more. I’ve got about 4ish spots left, so message me if you’d like some more details!! Dates are October 7-15 weekends in person. 🤙🏼🔥 25 CEU credits if you’re a Yoga Alliance Teacher 🤘🏻
